<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911021-0084</DOCNO><DOCID>911021-0084.</DOCID><HL>   Left-Wing Party Gains   In British Columbia Vote</HL><DATE>10/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><RE>CANADA (CN)NORTH AMERICA (NME)</RE><LP>   VANCOUVER, British Columbia -- The left-wing NewDemocratic Party won a decisive victory in an election forthe British Columbia legislature, defeating the conservativeSocial Credit Party which has ruled the province for the past16 years.   The New Democrats also are expected to win an electiontoday for the Saskatchewan legislature. The provincial wingof Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's Conservative Party hasbeen in power in Saskatchewan for nine years.</LP><TEXT>   In British Columbia, the New Democrats won 51 of the 75seats in the legislature, allowing them to form thegovernment. The party's leader is a former Vancouver mayor,Michael Harcourt, 48 years old.   He said after he election that New Democrats werecommitted to achieving their goals &quot;within a balancedbudget.&quot;   He also said, &quot;We have three simple rules that any goodcorporate citizen can follow: Treat employees fairly, don'tmess up the environment and pay your fair share of taxes.&quot; Ifcompanies follow those rules, he said &quot;we'll get along justfine.&quot;   The New Democrats have proposed a minimum tax onprofitable corporations and higher taxes on high-incomeearners. The party also intends eventually to ban log exportsby the province's big forest industry and to uphold amoratorium on offshore oil drilling.</TEXT></DOC>